# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brest-france
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The **1952 Tour de France** was the 39th edition of the Tour de France, taking place from 25 June to 19 July.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] It was composed of 23 stages over 4,807 km (2,987 mi).
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Newly introduced were the arrivals on mountain peaks.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The race was won by Italian Fausto Coppi.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Coppi dominated the race, winning five stages and the mountains classification, and was a member of the winning Italian team.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] His dominance was so large that the Tour organisation had to double the prize money for second place to make the race interesting.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] At the end, Coppi had a margin of almost half an hour over the second-ranked cyclist; such a margin has never been achieved again.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Although more than 25 years later during the 1979 edition, the 1st and 2nd-place finishers Bernard Hinault and Joop Zoetemelk were both nearly a half hour ahead of the 3rd-place finisher.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] As was the custom since the 1930 Tour de France, the 1952 Tour de France was contested by national and regional teams.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The three major cycling countries in 1952, Italy, Belgium and France, each sent a team of 12 cyclists.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Other countries sent teams of 8 cyclists: Switzerland, Luxembourg (together with Australia), Netherlands and Spain.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The French regional cyclists were divided into four teams of 12 cyclists: Paris, North-East/Centre, South-East and West/South-West.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The last team of eight cyclists was made up out of cyclists from the French North African colonies.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the end, Luxembourg only sent 6 cyclists, so altogether this made 122 cyclists.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] There were 57 French (of which 6 were Algerian), 13 Italian, 12 Belgian, 8 Dutch, 8 Spanish, 8 Swiss, 5 Luxembourgian and 1 Australian cyclists.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The winners of the last two editions, Swiss cyclists Hugo Koblet and Ferdinand Kübler, were injured and did not enter the race, nor did French cyclist Louison Bobet.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] On the last press conference before the race, Jacques Goddet conducted a poll amongst journalists to see who they considered the favourite.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Coppi received 29 votes in that poll, followed by Géminiani and Bartali, both with 26 votes.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The final stage was from Vichy, the capital of Vichy France in the Second World War, to Paris.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Vichy had never before been visited, and the distance from Vichy to Paris was significantly longer than the other stages.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] A newspaper described it as linking the two cities together.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The stop in Vichy was successful, with a new record of 150.000 live spectators.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] An innovation was the stage arrivals on mountain peaks.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] This happened three times in 1952, on stages 10, 11 and 21.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] There were two rest days, in Alpe d'Huez and Toulouse.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,556 m (8,386 ft) at the summit tunnel of the Col du Galibier mountain pass on stage 11.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the fourth stage, Jean Robic, the winner of the 1947 Tour de France was in a group with his teammate Raphaël Géminiani, and Robic let Géminiani do all the work.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] After the stage, Robic told reporters that he had been smart, because he had saved energy and was in a better position to win the Tour.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Géminiani then became angry and held Robic's head in a hotel room sink.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] It was the last year that Robic rode on the national team.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] At that moment, Nello Lauredi was the leader in the race.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the sixth stage, Fiorenzo Magni escaped, and became the leader of the general classification by twelve seconds.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the 1950 Tour de France, Magni had already become the leader, but left the race without riding in the yellow jersey.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the time trial in stage seven, won by Fausto Coppi, Magni lost his lead, and Lauredi became leader again.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The first high mountains appeared in stage eight.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Magni and Lauredi stayed together, but because Magni took a twenty-second bonification for finishing second, they swapped positions again, and Magni became leader again.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the ninth stage, a group of eight cyclists got away, including Coppi's teammate Andrea Carrea.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] At the end of the stage, the group had a margin of more than nine minutes.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Carrea went to the hotel after the finish, but was picked up by the police.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Carrea asked what he had done wrong, but he was told that he was the new leader of the race, and had to go to the ceremony to receive the yellow jersey.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Carrea apologised to his team leader Coppi, in fear that his team leader would be angry because a helper occupied the highest rank, but Coppi was not angry.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the tenth stage, Robic attacked, and only Coppi was able to follow him.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Because his team director was far away, he lost several minutes, and lost so much time that he dropped from second place to fifth place.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Coppi rode away and won the stage, taking over the lead in the general classification from his teammate.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The top three riders were all Italian at that moment.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] After the rest day, the eleventh stage was again a mountain stage.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The cyclists from the French national team, especially Géminiani, attacked on the Galibier, but Coppi counterattacked and escaped easily.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] At the end of the stage, Coppi won by a large margin.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] His lead in the general classification was now almost 20 minutes.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The margin was so large that Coppi didn't need to attack in the twelfth stage.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] When Coppi had a flat tire, his teammate Gino Bartali gave him his own wheel, which was a sign that the rivalry between the two cyclists was over.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Even though Coppi rode conservatively in that stage, the cyclist directly behind him in the general classification, Alex Close, lost another four minutes, and Coppi was now 24 minutes ahead.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The Tour organisation feared that the race would become dull, now that Coppi's lead was so large.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Therefore, they doubled the prize money for second and third place, hoping to keep the other cyclists aggressive.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the sixteenth stage, the riders were apparently not motivated by the double prize money, as they were slow that day.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The organisation then responded by canceling the prize money; there was still a rule from before 1947, that said that stage winners had to go at least 30 km/h to win prize money.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The winner, André Rosseel, had only reached 29 km/h.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the seventeenth stage, Géminiani, who was already in fourteenth place, 52 minutes behind in the general classification, escaped.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Coppi did not chase him, and allowed Géminiani to win the stage.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the eighteenth stage, Coppi reached the top of the mountains first, but took it easy on the descent, and allowed other cyclists to get back to him.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] He still won the sprint at the end of the stage.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Coppi also won the last mountain stage, stage 21, and increased his lead to more than 31 minutes.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] In the time trial on the next day, Coppi apparently took it easy.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Previously he was an expert in such time trials, but on that day he allowed other cyclists to win back some time, and finished on the fourteenth place.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The time that each cyclist required to finish each stage was recorded, and these times were added together for the general classification.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Of the 123 cyclists that started the 1951 Tour de France, 66 finished the race.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Points for the mountains classification were earned by reaching the mountain tops first.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The system was the same as in 1951: there were three types of mountain tops: the hardest ones, in category 1, gave 10 points to the winner, the easier ones in category 2 gave 6 points to the winner, and the easiest in category 3 gave 3 points.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The team classification had been awarded and calculated since 1930, but in 1952 the daily team classification was also calculated: for each stage, the best team (calculated as the team of which the best three cyclists had the lowest accumulated team in that stage) received a prize.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that led this classification wore yellow caps for the first time in 1952.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The Luxembourgian team finished with only two cyclists, and therefore were not eligible for the team classification.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The 1952 Tour de France saw the introduction of the combativity award, a daily award for the most combative rider of the stage.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The winner of that award received 100,000 French francs.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The super-combativity award, the award for the most combative rider of the entire Tour de France, was also first given in 1953, determined by a jury vote, to Robic.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given to the first rider to pass the memorial to Tour founder Henri Desgrange near the summit of the Col du Galibier stage 11.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The special award for the best regional rider was won by eighteenth-placed Marcel Zelasco.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] After every stage, an award was given to the cyclist with the most bad luck, and to the most 'cold-blooded' cyclist.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] At the end of the Tour the award for the cyclist with the most bad luck was given to Wim van Est.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The award for most beloved cyclist was given to Antonin Rolland.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The daily combativity award was a success, and has been awarded ever since.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The mountain finishes also were spectacular enough to have been included in every Tour de France since.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] Fausto Coppi would never start the Tour de France again.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] The team selectors for the French national team felt that Raphaël Géminiani had held back when chasing Fausto Coppi, because they rode for the same sponsor.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] For that reason, Géminiani was left out the national team for the 1952 UCI Road World Championships.
[src:brest-france/1952-tour-de-france] To avoid these problems in the future, Géminiani switched teams at the end of the season.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The **1974 Tour de France** was the 61st edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] It took place between 27 June and 21 July, with 22 stages covering a distance of 4,098 km (2,546 mi).
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Eddy Merckx was attempting to win his fifth Tour de France in as many races.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In 1974 the tour made its first visit to the United Kingdom, with a circuit stage on the Plympton By-pass, near Plymouth, England.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The race was won by favourite Eddy Merckx, who thus at that point had won all five Tours that he had entered, and had equalled Jacques Anquetil in Tour victories.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] While he won the race by a comfortable margin, he was not as overwhelmingly dominant as he had been in his previous victories with eight riders finishing within 20:00, two riders within 10:00 and his two top competitors in Luis Ocaña and Joop Zoetemelk absent from the race.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Despite other riders finishing closer in the overall standings, Merckx still won an astonishing eight stages.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] He also won the combination classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Fellow Belgian Patrick Sercu won the points classification, while Spanish Domingo Perurena won the mountains classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The 1974 Tour de France had 13 teams, with 10 cyclists each.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Eddy Merckx, who had been absent in 1973 after winning four Tours in a row, was present again.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx had not been as dominant in the spring as in other years; it was his first year as a professional cyclist in which he did not win a spring classic.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] He did win the 1974 Giro d'Italia and the Tour de Suisse, but after winning the latter he required surgery on the perineum, five days before the 1974 Tour started.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Notable absents were Ocaña and Zoetemelk.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Zoetemelk was injured during the Midi Libre and was in hospital with life-threatening meningitis.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Between 1970 and 1986 this would be the only Tour Zoetemelk would not start and finish, and would be the only Tour until 1983 that he was not in the top ten.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Ocaña had crashed in the Tour de l'Aude, gone home and was fired by his team for not communicating.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Bernard Thévenet, who was considered a potential winner, had crashed several times in the 1974 Vuelta a España.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] He did start in the Tour, but was not yet back at his former level.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The 1974 Tour de France started on 27 June, and had two rest days, in Aix-les-Bains and Colomiers.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx won the prologue, with his teammate Joseph Bruyère in third place.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In the first stage, Bruyère was part of a breakaway, and became the new leader.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The second stage was in Plymouth, the first time that the Tour de France visited England.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The riders did not like the experiment, as the British immigration officials made the cyclists wait for a long time when entering the country and again when returning to France.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx collected bonus time in the sprints, and in the fourth stage took back the leading position in the general classification, with Gerben Karstens in second place.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Karstens was also doing well in the points classification, and felt Merckx and Patrick Sercu, the leaders in the general and points classification, were helping each other.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Karstens was angry and after the finish quickly went away, but forgot that he had to go to the doping control.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] For this, he was given ten minutes penalty time, and thus he lost his second place in the general classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Karstens complained to the jury, and other cyclists threatened with a strike, so the jury removed the penalty after the fifth stage.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Thanks to bonification seconds in that stage, Karstens took the leading position after that stage.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] It was still close in the top of the general classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Patrick Sercu became the new leader after the first part of the sixth stage, but Karstens regained the lead after the second part of the sixth stage, a team time trial won by Merckx's team, Molteni.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx won the seventh stage, and became the next leader.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The Alps were the first serious mountains to be seen, in stage nine.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx won the stage, but the surprise of the day was Raymond Poulidor, who at 38 years old was still able to escape during the toughest part of the stage.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] This also happened in the tenth stage: Poulidor joined the crucial escape, but could not beat Merckx in the final sprint.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In the tenth stage, the hardest Alpine stage, Vicente López Carril from the KAS team stayed away.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx was in the next group, together with Francisco Galdós and Gonzalo Aja, also from the KAS team.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Aja was in third place in the general classification, so Merckx was unable to chase López Carril without helping his rival Aja.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The next stages did not change the general classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In the fifteenth stage, the Pyrenées were encountered.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] There was a crash that took down Galdós, now in sixth place in the general classification, and he had to leave the race.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The Tour was in Spain at that point, and Basque separatist placed bombs on press and team cars.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] There was violence around France, Andorra and in Corsica from unrelated protests including from farmers and other angry nationalists and in some areas people hung dead pigs from street lamps.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The bombings in the Pyrenees took place in the middle of the night in Lourdes where thirteen vacant buses and two parked cars where destroyed.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Then a few hours later at Saint-Lary-Soulan several vehicles associated with the Tour de France were targeted and blown up.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Leaflets were distributed threatening the fascist government of Spain and telling Spanish riders to leave the race.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Other acts of violence against the Tour included many trees being cut down to block the route, which had to be dealt with and removed.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Nobody was hurt, but cyclists were scared: Spanish champion López Carril did not wear his national champion's jersey, afraid to become a target because of the Spanish flag on it.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In the sixteenth stage, with an uphill finish, Poulidor won, his first Tour stage victory since 1965.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx finished in fourth place, losing time to Poulidor, López Carril and Pollentier.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In the seventeenth stage, Poulidor again won time, finishing second after Jean-Pierre Danguillaume, and jumped to the third place in the general classification, behind Merckx and López Carril.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Danguillaume also won the eighteenth stage, the last mountain stage.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The favourites stayed together with Merckx, and at that point Merckx was more or less certain of the victory, with two time trials remaining, in which he normally would gain time on the others.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Poulidor battled with López-Carril for the second place.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] After the time trial in the second part of stage 21, Poulidor captured the second place by just one second.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Surprisingly, Merckx was in second place in that time trial, beaten by Michel Pollentier.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In the last stage, Poulidor increased the margin to López Carril to five seconds due to bonus seconds in an intermediate sprint.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] At the finish of that last, Sercu finished first in a sprint, but he had blocked the way of Gustaaf Van Roosbroeck, so the jury decided to set him back, and the second rider to finish (Merckx) was declared winner of the stage.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Normally, a rider penalized for blocking another rider during a sprint would be set back to the last place of the group that he finished in, but that would have meant that Sercu would have not only lost the stage victory to Merckx, but also the points classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The jury then declared that only three riders were really sprinting for the stage victory, so Sercu would be set back to the third place; this enabled him to keep his victory in the points classification by 13 points.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Cyrille Guimard, who had won the first part of stage eight, tested positive for piperidine after stage thirteen.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Three other cyclists tested positive:Claude Tollet, for amphetamine; Daniel Ducreux, for piperidine; Carlos Melero, for piperidine.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] There were several classifications in the 1974 Tour de France, three of them awarding jerseys to their leaders.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The most important was the general classification, calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey; the winner of this classification is considered the winner of the Tour.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Additionally, there was a points classification, where cyclists got points for finishing among the best in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification, and was identified with a green jersey.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] There was also a mountains classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The organisation had categorised some climbs as either first, second, third, or fourth-category; points for this classification were won by the first cyclists that reached the top of these climbs first, with more points available for the higher-categorised climbs.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The cyclist with the most points lead the classification, but was not identified with a jersey in 1974.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Another classification was the combination classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] This classification was calculated as a combination of the other classifications, its leader wore the white jersey.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The fifth individual classification was the intermediate sprints classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] This classification had similar rules as the points classification, but only points were awarded on intermediate sprints.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In 1974, this classification had no associated jersey.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] For the team classification, the times of the best three cyclists per team on each stage were added; the leading team was the team with the lowest total time.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that led this classification were identified by yellow caps.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] There was also a team points classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Cyclists received points according to their finishing position on each stage, with the first rider receiving one point.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The first three finishers of each team had their points combined, and the team with the fewest points led the classification.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The riders of the team leading this classification wore green caps.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award, in which a jury composed of journalists gave points after certain stages to the cyclist they considered most combative.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The split stages each had a combined winner.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] At the conclusion of the Tour, Eddy Merckx won the overall super-combativity award, also decided by journalists.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange was given to the first rider to pass the memorial to Tour founder Henri Desgrange near the summit of the Col du Galibier on stage 11.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] This prize was won by Vicente López Carril.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] With his fifth Tour victory, Merckx equalled Jacques Anquetil.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Moreover, Merckx had won the first five Tours that he entered.
[src:brest-france/1974-tour-de-france] Merckx had already won the 1974 Giro d'Italia earlier that year, and after winning the 1974 Tour de France also won the world championship, and became the first cyclist to win the Triple Crown of Cycling.
[src:brest-france/1995-96-élite-ligue-season] The **1995–96 Élite Ligue season** was the 75th season of the Élite Ligue, the top level of ice hockey in France.
[src:brest-france/1995-96-élite-ligue-season] Eight teams participated in the league, and Albatros de Brest won their first league title.
[src:brest-france/1996-97-nationale-1a-season] The **1996–97 Nationale 1A season** was the 76th season of the Nationale 1A, the top level of ice hockey in France.
[src:brest-france/1996-97-nationale-1a-season] Eight teams participated in the league, and Albatros de Brest won their second league title.
[src:brest-france/1996-97-nationale-1a-season] Club des Sports de Megève, Gap Hockey Club, and Image Club d'Epinal were relegated to the Nationale 1B.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The **2008 Tour de France** was the 95th running of the race.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Starting in the French city of Brest, the tour entered Italy on the 15th stage and returned to France during the 16th, heading for Paris, its regular final destination, which was reached in the 21st stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Unlike previous years, time bonuses were no longer awarded for intermediate sprints and for high placement on each stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] This altered the way the General Classification was awarded in comparison to previous seasons.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Long running disputes between the event organisers, the ASO and the UCI reached a head when the race organisers insisted upon the right to invite, or exclude, whichever teams it chose for the event.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Under UCI rules, any ProTour event must be open to all member teams of the UCI's top level.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The ASO made it clear that, despite changes in team management and personnel, it intended to exclude Astana from the event as a result of its involvement in the doping scandals that marred the 2007 Tour and its links to the 2006 Operación Puerto doping case.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] This meant that the champion (Alberto Contador) and third-place finisher (Levi Leipheimer) from 2007, both of whom had since signed with Astana, could not compete in the 2008 Tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The ASO announced on 20 March 2008 that all ProTour teams except Astana would be invited, along with three wildcard teams: Agritubel, Barloworld, and Slipstream–Chipotle (subsequently renamed as Garmin–Chipotle p/b H30).
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] With each team consisting of nine riders, 180 riders started the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Because Astana was not invited to the 2008 Tour de France, the winner of the 2007 Tour de France, Alberto Contador, the 3rd-place finisher Levi Leipheimer and the 2004 and 2006 Tour de France runner up Andreas Klöden did not compete.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Ten days before the start of the tour, Contador picked Cadel Evans as the likely winner for 2008.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Shown in the table below are the riders that, according to the bookmakers in the months before the start of the 2008 Tour de France, had a chance of winning the 2008 Tour better than or equal to 25/1.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The odds shown are the odds in July 2008, directly before the start of the race.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Thomas Dekker and Michael Rogers were also given odds in this range, but were not included in the Tour de France.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The 2008 Tour de France was almost entirely in France, with only a small part in Italy.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In previous years, the Tour started with a prologue, followed by a week of flat stages.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The flat stages were dominated by the sprinters' teams, and the yellow jersey was worn by a sprinter who had a good prologue.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] At the presentation of the Tour de France 2008 schedule, Tour Director Christian Prudhomme announced that the 2008 Tour would be different: "We have wanted a first week of racing with much more rhythm.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was 2,802 m (9,193 ft) at the Cime de la Bonette loop road on stage 16.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In the first week of the 2008 Tour de France, the stages were mostly flat.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] As traditionally in the Tour de France, this resulted in small breakaways of cyclists, and the sprinters' teams trying to get them back.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In the first stage, the sprinters won, with Thor Hushovd winning the stage, but in the second stage, four cyclists managed to stay away.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The fourth stage was a time trial, won by Stefan Schumacher, who took over the lead.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In the fifth stage, the sprinters won the battle and Mark Cavendish won the stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The Massif Central mountains were visited in stage six and seven.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In stage six, all the breakaways were caught, and the favourites stayed together and finished together.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In stage seven, the same scenario, only now Luis León Sánchez managed to stay a few seconds ahead and win the stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The eighth stage was a sprinter stage, won by Cavendish.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Then, from stage nine, the Pyrenees were climbed.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Riccardo Riccò broke away from the bunch on the final climb, and won the stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On stage 10, a group of four with some main contenders escaped, and Leonardo Piepoli won the stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Stage eleven had easier climbs, and a group of four riders, not important for the overall classification, were allowed to break away and win by 14 minutes.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Stages twelve to fourteen were flat stages, and were dominated by the sprinters.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Mark Cavendish won another two stages, and Óscar Freire took his first.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In the fifteenth stage, a group of four cyclists escaped and stayed away, a similar thing happened in stage sixteen.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In the seventeenth stage, Carlos Sastre placed a surprise attack (not only a surprise for his opponents, but also for his teammates and directeur sportif) won the stage and took the lead in the general classification.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The eighteenth and nineteenth stage again saw breakaways of cyclists not important for the general classification.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The twentieth stage, a time trial, was won by Stefan Schumacher who had also won the first time trial.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The last stage was a sprinters' stage, won by Gert Steegmans.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 26 May 2008, the 2007 green jersey (points) winner Tom Boonen tested positive for cocaine.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Since this was outside competition, Boonen was not sanctioned by the UCI or WADA, but he was nevertheless barred from the 2008 Tour de France.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Following protracted disagreement between the organisers of the Tour de France (ASO) and the UCI, the race was sanctioned by the Fédération Française de Cyclisme (FFC), as was the 2008 Paris–Nice in March.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Thus the FFC were in charge of the doping controls before and during the race, and rather than increasing the number of doping controls during the Tour, they applied a more targeted approach on suspect riders.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The French government's anti-doping agency AFLD carried out approximately 60 random and targeted tests in the weeks leading up to the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] They took blood samples from all the 180 riders in a two-day period just before the first stage, and during the race took samples from up to 14 riders a day shortly after the stage was finished, 250 tests being run in total.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The Italian National Olympic Committee (CONI) also performed unannounced doping tests of riders at the finish of stage 15, which ended at the ski resort of Prato Nevoso, Italy.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 3 July 2008, France enacted a law criminalizing using or trafficking in doping substances.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 11 July news broke that Spanish rider Manuel Beltrán tested positive for erythropoietin after the first stage of the tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Blood abnormalities before the tour start had led AFLD to target the rider.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Beltrán's team Liquigas withdrew him from the tour with immediate effect.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] French law enforcement authorities questioned Beltrán over possible offences and searched his hotel room, but he claimed his innocence.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 13 July, prior to the ninth stage, it was revealed that AFLD had informed team doctors that five riders had unusually high hematocrit levels.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The Italian press reported that Riccardo Riccò, who won the stage later that day, had been selected for testing several times during the first week, which led to a suspicion that he was among those whose teams had been notified.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Riccò has for some time been known to have a naturally high hematocrit level of 51%, above the 50%-level which usually is taken to be an indicator of possible blood manipulation.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Riccò stated that he has a licence confirming that this is a natural, long-term condition, which he gave to the doping agencies before the start of the race, but he later admitted to the offence at a hearing of the Italian National Olympic Committee (CONI).
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 16 July Barloworld started the 11th stage without Moisés Dueñas, who had been withdrawn from the team after being tested positive for EPO at the end of the time trial fourth stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Barloworld Ltd, two days later, announced that they were withdrawing from sponsorship after this year's Tour de France, but on 28 October, they announced that they would sponsor the team for another year.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 17 July, shortly before the start of stage 12, Ricardo Riccò and the rest of the Saunier Duval–Scott team, withdrew from the race after the announcement that he had tested positive for MIRCERA, a new type of EPO, at the end of stage 4.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Leonardo Piepoli, winner of stage 10, was sacked by his team for "violation of the team's ethics code" the following day, though no positive test was reported at that time.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Almost 3 months later his tests came back positive for samples taken one day prior to the start of the Tour, on 4 July, and also on 15 July, on the rest day in Pau.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On the last day of the race, but after the end of the stage, Dmitry Fofonov was announced to have tested positive for the banned stimulant heptaminol after Stage 18.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] He was asked for a medical exemption to use the stimulant, but did not produce one.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] He was subsequently fired by his team Crédit Agricole.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] After the race ended, French cyclist Jimmy Casper was suspended from Agritubel because he tested positive after the stage to Super Besse for glucocorticoids, an asthma drug that is banned unless the user has a medical exemption for its use.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Casper, an asthmatic, carried a therapeutic use exemptions (TUE) for the last twelve years but failed to renew this exemption.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] His authorisation expired on 29 May and was not renewed before the 2008 Tour de France.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The French cycling federation's disciplinary commission exonerated Casper.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In late September it was announced that several Tour de France riders were to have their blood samples retested for traces of EPO.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Pierre Bordry, the head of AFLD, claimed the testing involved riders who were already under scrutiny for suspicious urine samples.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] AFLD had suspicion that there was MIRCERA in some samples but the laboratory could not say definitively.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The urine tests were somewhat unreliable at giving definitive results, so the AFLD decided to order the blood samples taken before and during the Tour for additional testing with a newly developed CERA blood test.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] As a result of this additional testing, both Leonardo Piepoli and Stefan Schumacher tested positive for the same substance which Riccò used, MIRCERA.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The riders were declared positive by AFLD.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] On 13 October 2008, the AFLD announced that Bernhard Kohl, who finished in third place overall and winner of the climbers' competition, had also tested positive for MIRCERA on 3 and 15 July, before and during the Tour de France.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Initial results were verified, and Kohl also confessed to doping.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] His third-place overall finish in the 2008 Tour and his first place in the King of the Mountains competition are considered vacancies in the Tour's official history.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] There were four main individual classifications contested in the 2008 Tour de France, as well as a team competition.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The most important was the general classification, which was calculated by adding each rider's finishing times on each stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] There were no time bonuses given at the end of stages for this edition of the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] If a crash had happened within the final 3 km (1.9 mi) of a stage, not including time trials and summit finishes, the riders involved would have received the same time as the group they were in when the crash occurred.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The rider with the lowest cumulative time was the winner of the general classification and was considered the overall winner of the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The rider leading the classification wore a yellow jersey.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The second classification was the points classification.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Riders received points for finishing in the highest positions in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints during the stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The points available for each stage finish were determined by the stage's type.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The leader was identified by a green jersey.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The third classification was the mountains classification.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Most stages of the race included one or more categorised climbs, in which points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit first.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The climbs were categorised as fourth-, third-, second- or first-category and *hors catégorie*, with the more difficult climbs rated lower.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The leader wore a white jersey with red polka dots.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The final individual classification was the young rider classification.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] This was calculated the same way as the general classification, but the classification was restricted to riders who were born on or after 1 January 1983.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The final classification was a team classification.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] This was calculated using the finishing times of the best three riders per team on each stage; the leading team was the team with the lowest cumulative time.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The number of stage victories and placings per team determined the outcome of a tie.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that lead this classification were identified with yellow number bibs on the back of their jerseys.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each mass start stage to the rider considered, by a jury, to have "made the greatest effort and who has demonstrated the best qualities of sportsmanship".
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] The winner wore a red number bib the following stage.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] At the conclusion of the Tour, Sylvain Chavanel (Cofidis) was given the overall super-combativity award.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Stefan Schumacher won the Henri Desgrange and Rémy Di Gregorio won the Jacques Goddet.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] A total prize fund of approximately €3.25 million was awarded throughout the tour.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] In addition, each team received €51,243 towards expenses of participation, with an additional €1,600 per rider who completed the race, provided that at least seven did so.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] By tradition, a team's winnings were pooled and shared among the riders and support team.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Team CSC, the team of Tour winner Sastre, won the most prize money, more than €600,000.
[src:brest-france/2008-tour-de-france] Saunier Duval's prize money was not awarded after the positive tests of Riccardo Riccò.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The **2018 Tour de France** was the 105th edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's three Grand Tours.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The 3,351 km (2,082 mi)-long race consisted of 21 stages, starting on 7 July in Noirmoutier-en-l'Île, in western France, and concluding on 29 July with the Champs-Élysées stage in Paris.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] A total of 176 riders from 22 teams participated in the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The overall general classification was won by Geraint Thomas of Team Sky.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Tom Dumoulin (Team Sunweb) placed second, with Thomas's teammate and four-time Tour winner Chris Froome coming third.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The opening stage was won by Fernando Gaviria of Quick-Step Floors, who became the Tour's first rider to wear the general classification leader's yellow jersey.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Peter Sagan (Bora–Hansgrohe) then took the race lead on the following stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] BMC Racing Team won stage three's team time trial, putting their rider Greg Van Avermaet in yellow.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He held the jersey for eight days until the second stage of the three Alpine stages, which Thomas won and took the lead in.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He successfully defended it from Dumoulin for the rest of the Tour, which included three stages in the Pyrenees and the penultimate stage's individual time trial, the latter won by Dumoulin.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Sagan, who won three stages, was placed first in the points classification for the sixth time.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Julian Alaphilippe of Quick-Step Floors, winner of two mountain stages, won the mountains classification, and AG2R La Mondiale's Pierre Latour won the young rider classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The team classification was won by Movistar Team, and Dan Martin of UAE Team Emirates won the combativity award.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The 2018 edition of the Tour de France consisted of 22 teams.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The race was the 25th of the 37 events in the UCI World Tour, and all of its eighteen UCI WorldTeams were entitled, and obliged, to enter the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] On 6 January 2018, organisers of the Tour, the Amaury Sport Organisation (ASO), announced the four second-tier UCI Professional Continental teams that received a wildcard invitation to participate in the event.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The four teams were Cofidis, Direct Énergie, Fortuneo–Samsic, from France, and Belgium's Wanty–Groupe Gobert, all of which have participated in the race before.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] This meant that new French team Vital Concept, with their team leader, sprinter Bryan Coquard, missed out on the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The presentation of the teams – where the members of each team's roster are introduced in front of the media and local dignitaries – took place on Place Napoleon in the town of La Roche-sur-Yon on 5 July, two days before the opening stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] New rules by the cycling's governing body, the *Union Cycliste Internationale* (UCI), reduced the number of riders per team for Grand Tours from 9 to 8, resulting in a start list total of 176, instead of 198, which had been the number of starters since 2010.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Of these, 35 competed in their first Tour de France.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Seven countries had more than 10 riders in the race: France (35), Belgium (19), the Netherlands (13), Italy (13), Australia (11), Germany (11) and Spain (11).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The average age of riders in the race was 29.37 years, ranging from the 21-year-old Egan Bernal (Team Sky) to the 40-year-old Franco Pellizotti (Bahrain–Merida).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Groupama–FDJ had the youngest average age while Bahrain–Merida had the oldest.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In the lead up to the Tour, the favourite for the general classification was Chris Froome of Team Sky.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Froome had won the 2013, 2015, 2016 and 2017 editions of the Tour, and was also the current defending champion at both other Grand Tours, the Vuelta a España and the Giro d'Italia.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] This was considered not as a positive doping result, but as an "Adverse Analytical Finding" (AAF), meaning that he was allowed to continue racing until the case was resolved.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He did however face the possibility of losing his Vuelta victory and all subsequent results.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The ASO were unhappy with the situation, which was very similar to that of the 2011 Tour pre-race favourite Alberto Contador, who started the tour with his case over a positive test for clenbuterol still unresolved.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The UCI conducted an investigation into the AAF, which was still unresolved at the time that Froome won the Giro in May 2018.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Froome was cleared by the UCI on 2 July, five days before the start of the Tour, with a press statement reading that the authorities had found sufficient evidence "that Mr Froome's sample results do not constitute an AAF".
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He was thereafter cleared to start the Tour by the ASO as well.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The closest rivals of Froome were thought to be Romain Bardet (AG2R La Mondiale), Tom Dumoulin (Team Sunweb), Mikel Landa (Movistar Team), Vincenzo Nibali (Bahrain–Merida), Richie Porte (BMC Racing Team), Nairo Quintana (Movistar Team) and Adam Yates (Mitchelton–Scott).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Porte's best result in the Tour was fifth overall in 2016.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He had shown his form so far in the 2018 season by winning the general classification of Tour de Suisse.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Although Quintana had placed twelfth overall in the 2017 Tour, his 2018 season so far had been consistent and he had finished second behind Froome in previous Tours.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He came to the Tour with a strong team, which included contender Landa, who in 2018 had moved to Movistar from Sky after being a domestique for Froome.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The 2017 Giro winner Dumoulin placed second in the 2018 Giro.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Nibali had recently won the classic Milan–San Remo, one of cycling's five one-day race "monuments".
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He had however failed to impress in the stage races leading up to the Tour, finishing 24th in the Critérium du Dauphiné after finishing outside the top 10 in the general classifications at Dubai Tour, Tour of Oman and the Tirreno–Adriatico.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He was the only rider on the start list apart from Froome to have won a Tour, the 2014 edition.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Bardet finished second and third overall in the two previous Tours and placed third in the Critérium du Dauphiné leading up to the 2018 Tour.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Yates' best overall Tour result was fourth 2016; he had shown his form during the season before the Tour with top-five placings in four stage races, including second in the Dauphiné.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Some of the other riders considered as contenders for the general classification were Dan Martin (UAE Team Emirates), Alejandro Valverde (Movistar Team), Rigoberto Urán (EF Education First–Drapac p/b Cannondale), Geraint Thomas (Team Sky) and Primož Roglič (LottoNL–Jumbo).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Others expected to contend for sprint finishes included Greg Van Avermaet (BMC Racing Team), Alexander Kristoff (UAE Team Emirates), Sonny Colbrelli (Bahrain–Merida), Nacer Bouhanni (Groupama–FDJ) and John Degenkolb (Trek–Segafredo).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Triple reigning world road race champion Sagan had won the five previous points classifications of the Tour before his 2017 Tour disqualification after race officials judged that he caused Cavendish to crash.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Sagan was again aiming to equal Erik Zabel's record of six points classifications.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] He was in good form during the season before the Tour, winning the one-day races Paris–Roubaix and Gent–Wevelgem, multiple top ten results one-day races and two points classifications in stage races.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Matthews, who won the 2017 Tour's points classification, suffered an early season injury and his sole win for the season was at the Tour de Romandie.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Kittel had won fourteen Tour stages, five in 2017, gained two wins so far in 2018, both at the Tirreno–Adriatico.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Debutant Gaviria had been second to Kittel at Quick-Step Floors before the latter moved to Team Katusha–Alpecin for the 2018 season.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Gaviria amassed a total of seven wins so far in 2018, and additionally the points classification at the Tour of California.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The 2011 points classification winner Cavendish's win at the Dubai Tour in February was his only of 2018 so far.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Winner of the 2017 Tour's final stage Groenewegen had a total of nine victories for the season going into the Tour, with one coming at Paris–Nice.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Démare, who led the points classification in the 2017 Tour, had gained two wins at Paris–Nice and the Tour de Suisse in 2018 before the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Greipel, who turned 36 during the Tour, had taken six wins at stage races during 2018 before the Tour, as well as the points classification of the Tour of Belgium.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] On 12 February 2017, at a rugby union match between France and Scotland at Paris's Stade de France, race director Christian Prudhomme announced the opening stages of the 2018 Tour (known as the *Grand Départ*) would take place in the Vendée department, in the Pays de la Loire region.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Since the inaugural Tour in 1903, the Vendée has hosted the *Grand Départ* five times, with the last in 2011.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Two weeks after the announcement, the ASO revealed that the *Grand Départ* would take place over three stages, with the third a team time trial.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In June 2017, the UCI's Professional Cycling Council (PCC) moved the start of the Tour a week later than usual and originally planned due to a clash with the 2018 FIFA World Cup.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The full route was announced on 17 October 2017; it was almost completely within France, with short deviations into Spain in the Pyrenees the only exceptions.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Two of the Tour's most historic climbs featured, Alpe d'Huez and the Col du Tourmalet, which last featured in 2015 and 2016 respectively.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Notable was stage nine's 21.7 km (13.5 mi) of sett paving, split across fifteen sectors, a feature that was last seen in the 2015 Tour.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] It finished in Roubaix, home of the "monument" race Paris–Roubaix.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] For the first time in 60 to 70 years, it included a section of unpaved roads on the Glières Plateau.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Overall, the route was thought to offer something for all rider types.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Stage one began in the village of Noirmoutier-en-l'Île on the island of Noirmoutier, before heading along the coast of the Vendée department.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The following two stages were loops, with the third taking the route north into the Maine-et-Loire department.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The next three stages took place in the region of Brittany, ending with two laps of the short, but steep, climb in Mûr-de-Bretagne.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The seventh, eighth and ninth stages headed north-east with finishes in Chartres, Amiens and Roubaix, respectively.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] A long transfer then moved the race to the Alps.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Following three stages in the mountains, the Tour descended into the Drôme department and stage thirteen's finish in the city of Valence.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The Massif Central highland region hosted stage fourteen, with the finish in Mende.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The next two transitional stages took the race south-west to the Pyrenees across a continuous journey between Millau, Carcassonne and Bagnères-de-Luchon.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] After two Pyrenean stages, the eighteenth stage took place in the foothills between Trie-sur-Baïse to Pau.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The next stage headed back into the mountains, before the penultimate stage, which took place close to the west coast in the French Basque Country.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] A long transfer took the Tour to its conclusion in Paris with the Champs-Élysées stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] There were 21 stages in the race, covering a total distance of 3,351 km (2,082 mi), the shortest of the 21st century up to that point.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] There were two time trial events, stage three's 35.5 km (22 mi) team time trial and stage twenty's 31 km (19 mi) individual time trial.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Of the remaining nineteen stages, eight were officially classified as flat, five as hilly and six as mountainous.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The longest mass-start stage was stage seven, at 231 km (144 mi), and the shortest was stage seventeen, at 65 km (40 mi).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The aforementioned, a mountain stage, was the shortest since 1996 and began with a standing start grid formation, with positions based on riders general classification ranking.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The grid formation was an innovation for the Tour, and with shorter distance, was beforehand universally welcomed, but it was thought to have made little effect on the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] There were summit finishes on three stages, stage eleven to La Rosière, stage twelve to Alpe d'Huez, and stage seventeen to the Col de Portet.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The highest point of elevation in the race was the 2,215 m (7,267 ft)-high Col de Portet Pyrenean pass, the first time it had been used in the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] It was among nine *hors catégorie* (English: "beyond category") rated climbs in the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] There were nine new stage start or finish locations.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The rest days were after stage nine, in Annecy, and fifteen, in Carcassonne.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Stage one's bunch sprint was won by Fernando Gaviria, with Peter Sagan coming in second place and Marcel Kittel in third.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Gaviria took the yellow and green jerseys as the leader of the general and points classifications respectively.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Breakaway rider Kévin Ledanois (Fortuneo–Samsic) collected the most mountains classification points to take the first polka dot jersey as the leader of the classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Sagan won stage two from a sprint to take the yellow and green jerseys, with Dion Smith of Wanty–Groupe Gobert claiming the lead in the mountains classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Stage four was won by Gaviria from a bunch sprint.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Sagan further extended his lead in the points competition by winning stage five's uphill sprint finish in Quimper.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Also in stage five, Toms Skujiņš of Trek–Segafredo won the mountains points which gave him the polka dot jersey, becoming the first from Latvia to ever lead the mountains classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In stage six, which ended atop the Mûr-de-Bretagne climb, Dan Martin attacked with a kilometre remaining and was able to stay away take the victory one second ahead of a large group that the contained the general classification contenders.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In the closing kilometres of the stage, Geraint Thomas won a three-second time bonus sprint that brought him to three seconds behind Van Avermaet in the general classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Overall favourites Romain Bardet and Tom Dumoulin lost time as their tyres punctured late in the stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The seventh stage was won by Dylan Groenewegen from a bunch sprint.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] There were multiple crashes in the first week of the Tour with six riders abandoning the race for various reasons, including the 2017 Tour points classification winner Michael Matthews.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Groenewegen won a further bunch sprint in the eighth stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In the sprint, André Greipel and Gaviria were penalised for headbutting each other and lost their stage placing and green jersey points.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Stage nine's sett-paving sections caused many issues for the riders, including leading sprinters and two of the classification contenders.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Richie Porte abandoned for the second year in a row after crashing in the opening 10 km (6.2 mi).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Rigoberto Urán initially tried to continue the race despite injuries sustained during a crash, but was forced to quit the race on the following stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Chris Froome, his teammate Egan Bernal, Jakob Fuglsang, and Mikel Landa, crashed in the stage along with many other riders; numerous riders had tyre punctures as well, including three for Bardet.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] His teammate Alexis Vuillermoz was forced to abandon the stage after colliding with a spectator taking photographs.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Meanwhile, Yves Lampaert (Quick-Step Floors), John Degenkolb, and Van Avermaet were able escape the remaining riders from the peloton (main group) and together they contested a sprint finish, which was won by Degenkolb.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Van Avermaet gained time, as well winning the time bonus sprint, to extend his lead in the general classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The following day was the Tour's first rest day.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The first stage in the high mountains and first in the Alps, the tenth, was won by Quick-Step Floors rider Julian Alaphilippe, who attacked on his own with 30 km (18.6 mi) to go from a large breakaway group that included race leader Van Avermaet.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The aforementioned retained the yellow jersey and extended his lead to 2 min 22 s, when pundits predicted the first day in the Alps would be his last as overall race leader.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Alaphilippe also took lead of the mountains classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Thomas achieved back-to-back wins both from the group of overall contenders on stages eleven and twelve by pushing the breakaway riders until the very end.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In the steep summit finish of the eleventh, Thomas attacked in the final 1 kilometre (0.6 miles), passing lone breakaway rider Mikel Nieve (Mitchelton–Scott) and managed to distance himself from Froome and Dumoulin by twenty seconds to take the win.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] On the twelfth stage, which was the final day in the Alps, Thomas won the sprint on the flat finish after the climb to Alpe d'Huez.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] LottoNL–Jumbo's Steven Kruijswijk was caught by the group of overall contenders in the final kilometres after he had launched a solo attack with 70 km (43.5 mi) remaining.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Following the stage, the general classification top three was: Thomas in first position, Froome second, 1 min 39 s down, and Dumoulin third, a further 11 seconds behind.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] General classification contender Vincenzo Nibali, who was fourth overall, was forced to withdraw from the Tour following the stage after an incident near the summit of Alpe d'huez where he fell off his bike fracturing a vertebra taking Roglič down with him.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] It was initially suspected that the crash had been caused by a police motorcycle driving in front of him, but it later emerged that he became caught in a spectator's camera strap.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Nibali's team management saw the lack of crowd control from the police and spectators lighting flares as contributing factors.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Following the incident, Christian Prudhomme appealed to fans to show the riders more respect.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Many riders left the Tour during the Alpine stages, either being forced to abandon due to fatigue and injury, or were disqualified for finishing outside the cut-off time; riders of note were the sprinters Mark Cavendish, Gaviria, Greipel, Groenewegen, and Kittel.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Sagan won stage thirteen with a surprise attack in the closing meters of the bunch sprint finish, while Alexander Kristoff and Arnaud Démare were together sprinting for the finish line.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In stage fourteen, Omar Fraile of Astana launched a late move from the large breakaway after the final climb to win at the Mende aerodrome; the breakaway finished eighteen minutes ahead of the peloton.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Stage fifteen, the start of the final week, was once again a breakaway victory, with Magnus Cort taking Astana's second win in two days.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The next day was the second rest day of the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Following the stage, controversy arose around Team Sky rider Gianni Moscon, who had allegedly punched Fortune-Samsic rider Élie Gesbert during the opening part of the stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] After reviewing footage of the incident, the race jury disqualified him for 'particularly serious aggression'.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] A non-racing incident occurred during the sixteenth stage when hay bales were placed across the road by local farmers protesting about reductions to their subsidies.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The police used tear gas to disperse them, and as the riders rode past this area, there was still gas in the air.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The race was subsequently neutralized for about fifteen minutes because several riders had problems with their eyes and had to rinse them.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] After the restart, a large breakaway escaped, and Philippe Gilbert (Quick-Step Floors), while in the lead on a descent, lost control of his bicycle and crashed into and over a wall.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Later, Adam Yates, having taken the lead, also fell.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Gilbert finished the stage and collected the most combative rider award, but would not start the following day.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Yates carried on, but was overtaken by Alaphilippe, who took his second stage victory.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The first of three stages in the Pyrenees, the seventeenth, opened with an uneventful grid formation, which saw the customary early formation of a breakaway group.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Froome's challenge faded on the approach to the summit of the Col de Portet and he dropped to third position in the general classification, 2 min 31 s behind Thomas.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Dumoulin moved into second place, 1 min 59 s off the lead.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Nairo Quintana won the stage after attacking at the bottom of the final climb, moving himself up to fifth overall, behind Primož Roglič.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The flat stage eighteen was won by Démare from a bunch sprint.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] By this point of the Tour, most of the top sprinters had left, and Démare had come close to missing the time cut in the previous stage along with Sagan, who had crashed heavily and was suffering with injuries.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] On the mountainous stage nineteen, Roglič attacked on the descent following the final climb, to a misty Col d'Aubisque, and soloed to the finish line nineteen seconds ahead of the chasing small group of overall favourites.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Thomas was able to consolidate his overall position by picking up six bonus seconds by winning the sprint for second place, thereby extending his lead over Dumoulin to 2 min 5 s.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The penultimate stage's 31 km (19.3 mi) individual time trial was won by Dumoulin, who finished one second ahead of Froome.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Froome in turn managed to retake third place from Roglič.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Thomas came third after surviving a scare when his back wheel locked, but completed the stage successfully, finishing fourteen seconds behind Dumoulin, taking a lead of 1 min 51 s into the final stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The final stage in Paris was won by Kristoff in a bunch sprint on the Champs-Élysées.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Thomas won the race with no changes in the final stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Froome came third overall, 2 min 24 s down on Thomas.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Sagan won the points classification with a total of 477, 231 ahead of Kristoff in second.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Alaphilippe won the mountains classification with 169 points, with the 2017 winner and French compatriot Warren Barguil (Fortuneo–Samsic) second with 80 points.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The best young rider was thirteenth-placed overall Pierre Latour (AG2R La Mondiale), with fifteenth-placed overall Bernal second.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Movistar Team finished as the winners of the team classification, 12 min 33 s ahead of second-placed Team Sky.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Of the 176 starters, 145 reached the finish of the last stage in Paris.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Four main individual classifications were contested in the 2018 Tour de France, as well as a team competition.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The most important was the general classification, calculated by adding each rider's finishing times on each stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Time bonuses (time subtracted) were awarded at the end of every stage apart from the time trial stages.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The first three riders received 10, 6, and 4 seconds, respectively.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Time bonuses of three, two and one seconds, were given to the first three riders to cross a "bonus point" in each of the first nine mass-start stages of the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] It would affect the general, but not the points classification.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] For crashes within the final 3 km (1.9 mi) of a stage, not including time trials and summit finishes, any rider involved received the same time as the group he was in when the crash occurred.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The rider with the lowest cumulative time was the winner of the general classification and was considered to be the overall winner of the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Riders received points for finishing among the highest placed in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints during the stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit of the most difficult climbs first.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The climbs were categorised, in order of increasing difficulty, as fourth-, third-, second-, and first-category and *hors catégorie*.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Double points were awarded at the top of the last mountains in the three mountain stages in the three Pyreneean stages (the Col du Portillon, the Col de Portet and the Col d'Aubisque).
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] This was calculated the same way as the general classification, but was restricted to riders born on or after 1 January 1993.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The riders on the team that lead this classification are identified with yellow number bibs on the back of their jerseys and yellow helmets.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each stage to the rider considered, by a jury, to have "made the greatest effort and who demonstrated the best qualities of sportsmanship".
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] No combativity awards were given for the time trials and the final stage.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] At the conclusion of the Tour, Dan Martin won the overall super-combativity award which was, again, awarded by a jury.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] A total of €2,287,750 was awarded in cash prizes in the race.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The overall winner of the general classification received €500,000, with the second and third placed riders getting €200,000 and €100,000 respectively.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] All finishers in the top 160 were awarded money.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The holders of the classifications benefited on each stage they led; the final winners of the points and mountains were given €25,000, while the best young rider and most combative rider got €20,000.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The team classification winners were given €50,000. €11,000 was given to the winners of each stage of the race, with smaller amounts given to places 2–20.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] There were also two special awards each with a prize of €5000.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] The Souvenir Henri Desgrange, given to first rider to pass the summit of the highest climb in the Tour, the Col du Portet on stage seventeen, and the Souvenir Jacques Goddet, given to the first rider to pass Goddet's memorial at the summit of the Col du Tourmalet in stage nineteen.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p01] Nairo Quintana won the Henri Desgrange and Julian Alaphilippe won the Jacques Goddet.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p02] Riders from the WorldTeams competed individually and for their teams for points that contributed towards the World Tour rankings.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p02] Riders from both the WorldTeams and Professional Continental teams also competed individually and for their nations for points that contributed towards the UCI World Ranking, which included all UCI road races.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p02] Both rankings used the same points scale, awarding points to the top sixty in the general classification, each yellow jersey given at the end of a stage, the top five finishers in each stage and for the top three in the final points and mountains classifications.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p02] The points accrued by Thomas moved him from 20th to second in the World Tour individual ranking and from 41st to fourth in the individual World Ranking.
[src:brest-france/2018-tour-de-france-p02] Sagan kept his position at the top of both rankings, with Quick-Step Floors and Belgium also holding the lead of the World Tour team ranking and World Ranking nation ranking respectively.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The **2021 Tour de France** was the 108th edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's three grand tours.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Originally planned for the Danish capital of Copenhagen, the start of the 2021 Tour (known as the *Grand Départ*) was transferred to Brest because of the COVID-19 pandemic, with Copenhagen hosting four matches in the UEFA Euro 2020, which had also been rescheduled to 2021 because of the pandemic.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Originally scheduled for 2 to 25 July 2021, the Tour was moved to 26 June to 18 July 2021 to avoid the rescheduled 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] This would have been the first occasion on which the Tour de France had visited Denmark.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Denmark instead hosted the *Grand Départ* in 2022.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The race was won for the second consecutive year by Tadej Pogačar of UAE Team Emirates, becoming the youngest rider to win the Tour twice.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar began to build his advantage with his win in the stage 5 time trial.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He first took the *maillot jaune* on stage 8, when he gained almost three and a half minutes on the other contenders after attacking on the penultimate climb of the Col de Romme.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He gained another half minute the next day on the summit finish to Tignes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar rode defensively in the second week before winning both mountaintop finishes at Col de Portet and Luz Ardiden in the third week.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He won by 5' 20" over Jonas Vingegaard of Team Jumbo–Visma.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Vingegaard was originally supposed to be a domestique for his team's original leader, Primož Roglič.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] After Roglič's crash and eventual abandon, Vingegaard became the team's leader and rode into form in the second week.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He managed to finish second on both mountaintop finishes in the third week before finishing third in the final time trial.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Third place went to Richard Carapaz of INEOS Grenadiers, becoming the first Ecuadorian to finish on the podium in the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He emerged as one of the three strongest climbers in the race, along with Pogačar and Vingegaard, before eventually finishing third on both summit finishes in the final week.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the race's other classifications, Mark Cavendish of Deceuninck–Quick-Step won the points classification for the second time in his career.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Cavendish took the green jersey after winning his first Tour stage since 2016 on stage 4.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He proceeded to win three more stages to equal Eddy Merckx's record for the most career Tour stage wins.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Aside from winning the *maillot jaune*, Pogačar also won the mountains and young rider classifications for the second successive year.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He clinched the win in the mountains classification after his back-to-back wins in the third week, adding 80 points to his tally as both stages' final climbs offered double points.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He took the lead in the young rider classification after the first stage and held on to the lead until the end of the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Team Bahrain Victorious won the team classification while Franck Bonnamour of B&B Hotels p/b KTM won the race's overall combativity award after being involved in several breakaways.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] 23 teams took part in the 2021 Tour de France.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] All 19 UCI WorldTeams were entitled and obliged to enter the race, and they were joined by four second-tier UCI ProTeams.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Alpecin–Fenix, the best performing UCI ProTeam in 2020, received an automatic invitation, while the other three teams were selected by Amaury Sport Organisation (ASO), the organisers of the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The teams were announced on 4 February 2021.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Usually, only twenty-two teams would participate in the race, but for the 2021 season, the Union Cycliste Internationale is allowing the total number of riders to increase from the normal 176 to 184.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With team sizes still set at eight riders, the decision allows grand tour organizers to invite one extra wildcard team.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the lead up to the 2021 Tour de France, Tadej Pogačar (UAE Team Emirates) and Primož Roglič (Team Jumbo–Visma) were seen by many pundits as the top pre-race favourites for the general classification.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Their closest rivals were considered to be the trio of Geraint Thomas, Richard Carapaz and Richie Porte from INEOS Grenadiers.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar was the defending champion and came into the 2021 edition with a successful start to the season, winning the overall classification at Tirreno–Adriatico and the Tour of Slovenia, finishing third at the Tour of the Basque Country, and winning his first Monument at Liège–Bastogne–Liège.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] After finishing as the Tour runner-up to Pogačar in 2020, Roglič went on to defend his overall title at the 2020 Vuelta a España.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In 2021, Roglič finished fifteenth at Paris–Nice before claiming the overall classification at the Tour of the Basque Country.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Thomas, the 2018 Tour champion, won the Tour de Romandie before finishing third overall in the lead-up Critérium du Dauphiné which was won by his teammate Porte.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Their teammate Carapaz, the 2019 Giro d'Italia champion, won the other lead-up race, the Tour de Suisse.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In February 2019, it was announced that Denmark would host the **Grand Départ** of the Tour in 2021.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] However, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, this was delayed to 2022.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The route for the 2021 Tour de France was announced by Christian Prudhomme on 1 November 2020, during France Télévisions' *Stade 2* programme.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The race covered a distance of 3,414 kilometres (2,121 miles), and saw its longest stage since the 2000 Tour de France, with 249.1 kilometres (154.8 miles) on stage seven.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The first stage featured a hilly course from Brest to Landerneau, with the finish situated atop the climb of Côte de la Fosse aux Loups.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A group of six broke away from the peloton, taking a lead of four minutes before Ide Schelling (Bora–Hansgrohe) attacked on the fourth climb of the day, the Côte de Stang ar Garront.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The rest of the break were caught before the intermediate sprint, where Schelling took maximum points before Caleb Ewan (Lotto–Soudal) outsprinted Peter Sagan (Bora–Hansgrohe) for second.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 45 kilometres (28 mi) to go, time trial ace Tony Martin (Team Jumbo–Visma) was brought down by a spectator who was holding a sign greeting her grandparents for TV cameras facing forward, and therefore unaware of the incoming peloton.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Triggered by the fall of Tony Martin, over 50 cyclists (most of the entire Stage 1 lineup) tripped over each other and crashed over the road, forming a massive pile-up that completely blocked the path for the ones at the back who didn't fall down.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Of the remaining ones that finished Schelling was caught with 27 kilometres (17 mi) left, but the KOM points he gained ensured that he wore the polka-dot jersey at the end of the day.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 7.5 kilometres (4.7 mi) to go, a touch of wheels caused another massive crash, delaying some GC contenders and causing them to lose minutes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the final climb, Julian Alaphilippe (Deceuninck–Quick-Step) attacked and immediately created a gap over the rest of the peloton.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He kept his advantage all the way to the line, winning the stage and taking the *maillot jaune* and the green jersey.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The second stage featured another uphill finish as the riders climbed the Mûr-de-Bretagne twice.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Six riders broke away from the peloton, building an advantage of four minutes before Deceuninck–Quick-Step began to chase the break.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the third climb of the day, Edward Theuns (Trek–Segafredo) attacked from the break, with Jérémy Cabot (Team TotalEnergies) the only other rider to respond to his attack.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Both riders were eventually caught ahead of the first passage of the Mûr-de-Bretagne.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Mathieu van der Poel (Alpecin–Fenix) attacked from the peloton, allowing him to gain eight bonus seconds before being caught on the descent.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the second ascent of Mûr-de-Bretagne, van der Poel attacked again just inside the *flamme rouge*.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He maintained his advantage to the line, winning the stage by six seconds over Tadej Pogačar (UAE Team Emirates) and Primož Roglič (Team Jumbo–Visma).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Geraint Thomas (INEOS Grenadiers) was gapped on the climb, finishing 17 seconds behind the two Slovenians.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] As a result of his gap and bonus seconds, van der Poel took the *maillot jaune* as well as the polka-dot jersey.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The third stage featured the first opportunity for the sprinters to come to the fore.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The break included five riders, leading by as much as three minutes before being chased.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] 37 kilometres (23 mi) into the stage, a crash in the peloton brought down Geraint Thomas (INEOS Grenadiers) and Robert Gesink (Team Jumbo–Visma), with the latter eventually having to abandon the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Thomas suffered a dislocated shoulder but he managed to continue and eventually made it back to the peloton.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) to go, Roglič crashed in the peloton, suffering from road rashes on the left side of his body.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Another crash took place with 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) to go, causing Jack Haig (Team Bahrain Victorious), who sat in sixth place on the GC, to abandon the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The crash also held up some contenders, including Pogačar.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the final sprint to the line, Ewan went down following a touch of wheels, also taking down Peter Sagan (Bora–Hansgrohe) in the process.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Ewan had to abandon the race while Sagan was able to finish the stage.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the aftermath, Tim Merlier (Alpecin–Fenix) won the sprint ahead of his teammate, Jasper Philipsen.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van der Poel escaped the crashes to retain the *maillot jaune* while Richard Carapaz (INEOS Grenadiers) also finished in the front group.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar's group lost 26 seconds while Roglič lost almost a minute and a half.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The crashes led to the peloton staging a brief protest before the start of the next stage.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The fourth stage featured another sprint stage, with the break featuring Brent Van Moer (Lotto–Soudal) and Pierre-Luc Périchon (Cofidis).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van Moer dropped Périchon with 15 kilometres (9.3 mi) left and still led by a minute with 7.5 kilometres (4.7 mi) to go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van Moer would be caught near the finish, where Mark Cavendish (Deceuninck–Quick-Step) outsprinted Nacer Bouhanni (Arkéa–Samsic) to win his first Tour stage since 2016.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Cavendish took the green jersey while the GC remained unchanged ahead of the first time trial.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The fifth stage featured a 27.2-kilometre (16.9 mi) individual time trial.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Mikkel Bjerg (UAE Team Emirates) set the early benchmark time of 33' 01" before being beaten by Mattia Cattaneo (Deceuninck–Quick-Step), who was six seconds faster than Bjerg.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Cattaneo was immediately beaten by Stefan Küng (Groupama–FDJ), who set a time of 32' 19".
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] His time stood at the top until Pogačar set the quickest time at both time checks before beating Küng's time by 19 seconds.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar kept the lead to win the stage and taking significant time from the other contenders.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The *maillot jaune*, van der Poel, took fifth place, 31 seconds behind Pogačar, to keep the race lead by eight seconds over the Slovenian.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The sixth stage featured another chance for the sprinters, where Cavendish outsprinted Philipsen to win his second stage of the race and his 32nd overall Tour stage win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The seventh stage featured the longest stage of the race with a 249.1-kilometre (154.8 mi) course from Vierzon to Le Creusot.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A large 29-man break, including van der Poel and Wout van Aert (Team Jumbo–Visma), went away with 200 kilometres (120 mi) to go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] UAE Team Emirates tried to chase down the break but gap continued to gradually increase to more than six minutes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With around 87.5 kilometres (54.4 mi) to go, Matej Mohorič (Team Bahrain Victorious) attacked from the break together with Van Moer.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] They would be joined by other riders before Mohorič soloed off the front on the steepest climb of the day, the Signal d'Uchon.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He managed to keep his lead to win the stage by 1' 20" over Jasper Stuyven (Trek–Segafredo) as well as taking the polka-dot jersey.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van der Poel and van Aert finished in the third group at 20 seconds further in arrears as van der Poel kept the *maillot jaune*.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the peloton, Roglič began to struggle on the climb of Signal d'Uchon, eventually losing more than three minutes to the other contenders.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Near the top, Carapaz attacked while Pogačar did not respond to the move.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He led by as much as 40 seconds before Movistar Team chased him down, eventually catching him at the finish.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The race went into the Alps on the eighth stage, with the riders tackling three first-category climbs before a descent into Le Grand-Bornand.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] At the start of the stage, Roglič and Thomas were unable to follow the pace, eventually conceding more than 35 minutes and ending their chances for Tour victory.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A break was soon established with 77 kilometres (48 mi) to go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Just before the second category-one climb of Col de Romme, the Team DSM duo of Søren Kragh Andersen and Tiesj Benoot attacked from the break.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] They were soon passed by Michael Woods (Israel Start-Up Nation), who led by a minute over the chase group.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the peloton, van der Poel began to struggle on the Col de Romme as UAE Team Emirates started to set a furious pace.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Four kilometres to the top of the Romme, Pogačar launched an attack, and only Carapaz could follow.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar launched another acceleration a few seconds later, dropping Carapaz and gradually building his gap over the other contenders.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Up front, on the final climb of Col de la Colombière, Woods started to fade and he was soon caught and dropped by Dylan Teuns (Team Bahrain Victorious).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] From behind, Pogačar passed the remnants of the breakaway and he came to within 15 seconds of catching Teuns at the top of the Colombière.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar avoided taking risks on the descent, allowing Teuns to increase his advantage.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Teuns held on to win the stage while Pogačar gained almost three and a half minutes on the other contenders.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] As a result, Pogačar took the *maillot jaune*, almost two minutes ahead of van Aert and almost five minutes ahead of the other contenders.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Stage nine featured the race's first mountaintop finish as the riders headed to Tignes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Before the start of the stage, Roglič and van der Poel announced their abandonment from the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A large 41-man break attacked while the peloton allowed them an advantage of more than eight minutes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Three riders eventually emerged as the strongest in the break, with Ben O'Connor (AG2R Citroën Team), Sergio Higuita (EF Education–Nippo), and Nairo Quintana (Arkéa–Samsic) were left at the front of the race as they began the final climb of Monteé de Tignes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] O'Connor soon dropped both Quintana and Higuita, who both faded on the rest of the climb.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] O'Connor eventually soloed to the stage win by more than five minutes ahead.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the peloton, UAE Team Emirates controlled for much of the day before INEOS Grenadiers took over on the final climb.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With around 2 kilometres (1.2 mi) to the top of the climb, Carapaz attacked, with Pogačar immediately responding.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Shortly afterwards, Pogačar accelerated himself, dropping all his rivals and gaining 32 seconds over a group containing Carapaz, Jonas Vingegaard (Team Jumbo–Visma), Enric Mas (Movistar Team), and Rigoberto Urán (EF Education–Nippo).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the GC, Pogačar held a lead of more than two minutes over O'Connor while the rest of the contenders were more than five minutes behind.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van Aert, who sat in second at the start of the day, lost more than 31 minutes on the stage.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The first day after the rest day offered another chance for the sprinters.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Hugo Houle (Astana–Premier Tech) and Tosh Van der Sande (Lotto–Soudal) established the day's main breakaway, but both riders were caught with around 36 kilometres (22 mi) to go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Several teams attempted to split the peloton in the crosswinds but no contenders were caught out.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the final sprint, Deceuninck–Quick-Step perfectly led out Cavendish for his third stage win and his 33rd career Tour stage win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The race headed back into the mountains on the eleventh stage, with the riders tackling the Mont Ventoux twice before a descent into Malaucène.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Two separate groups broke away from the peloton, with second group eventually joining the riders up front.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the first ascent of the Ventoux, Alaphilippe led an attack that split the break into two.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] At the bottom of the second ascent of the Ventoux, Kenny Elissonde (Trek–Segafredo) attacked the break while a chase group composed of Alaphilippe, van Aert, and Bauke Mollema (Trek–Segafredo) formed behind.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van Aert soon bridged up to Elissonde before dropping him while Mollema dropped Alaphilippe.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Van Aert gradually built his advantage to solo to the stage win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] From behind, INEOS Grenadiers controlled the peloton for much of the day.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] At the bottom of the second ascent of the Ventoux, O'Connor began to struggle, eventually losing more than four minutes on the day.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] INEOS Grenadiers continued to splinter the GC group until Vingegaard attacked 2 kilometres (1.2 mi) from the top.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar followed his move before getting dropped by the Dane shortly afterwards.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Vingegaard led by almost 40 seconds at the top while Pogačar, Carapaz, and Urán joined on the descent.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The trio managed to work together to bring back Vingegaard near the *flamme rouge*.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the GC, Pogačar's advantage over second place increased to more than five minutes as Urán moved up to second.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The twelfth and thirteenth stage featured chances for the sprinters.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In stage 12, several teams attempted to split the race into echelons at the start of the stage, with the peloton splitting into three groups.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A group of 13 soon went off the front while the peloton eased off and allowed the two other groups to rejoin the main peloton.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] No teams took up the chase as the break continued to extend their advantage.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 50 kilometres (31 mi) to go, Nils Politt (Bora–Hansgrohe) started the attacks but he was chased down.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A few kilometres later, Politt attacked again, this time with Küng, Harry Sweeny (Lotto–Soudal), and Imanol Erviti (Movistar Team).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Politt emerged as the strongest from the break, dropping his companions to solo to the stage win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The peloton finished around 16 minutes down.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Stage 13 featured another threat of crosswinds in the final part of the course but the winds were not strong enough to form echelons.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 62 kilometres (39 mi) to go, a crash on a descent took out several riders at the back of the peloton, with other riders also falling down a small ravine.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] No riders were seriously hurt but the crash led to several abandons.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In a messy sprint to the line, Michael Mørkøv (Deceuninck–Quick-Step) led out Cavendish, who won his fourth stage of the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] His 34th career Tour win meant that he tied Eddy Merckx's record for the most number of Tour stage wins.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The fourteenth stage featured a transition stage as the race began to head into Andorra and the Pyrenees.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] It would take almost 100 kilometres (62 mi) for a breakaway to be fully established.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A 14-man break went off the front of the peloton, including Woods and Wout Poels (Team Bahrain Victorious) who were vying for the polka-dot jersey.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The break also included Guillaume Martin (Cofidis), who started the day in ninth place on the GC.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On one of the descents, Woods slid out on a bend but he managed to rejoin the break.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 42 kilometres (26 mi) to go and still on the descent, Mollema attacked off the front.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He gained an advantage of more than a minute over his breakaway companions ahead of the final climb of the Col de Saint-Louis.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He maintained his advantage to solo to the stage win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Woods took the polka-dot jersey from Quintana while Martin moved up to second overall.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Mattia Cattaneo (Deceuninck–Quick-Step) also took enough time to move into the top ten.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The other contenders remained together in preparation of the mountainous stage to Andorra.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the fifteenth stage, the race headed to Andorra and passing over the Port d'Envalira, the highest point in the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A large 32-rider group broke away from the peloton, eventually extending their advantage to around 10 minutes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The break included Woods, Poels, van Aert, and Quintana, who were all battling for the KOM competition.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Woods and Poels were both neck and neck at the top before Poels soon took the lead to take the polka-dot jersey.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Near the top of the Port d'Envalira, Quintana attacked to take the Souvenir Henri Desgrange, given to the first rider across the highest point in the Tour.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Quintana would be caught on the descent.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the last climb of the day, the Col de Beixalis, Sepp Kuss (Team Jumbo–Visma) launched his move 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) from the top.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Only Alejandro Valverde (Movistar Team) was able to follow his move before he began to struggle following Kuss.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Kuss managed to hold off Valverde to win the stage.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the peloton, Martin and Cattaneo, two riders in the top ten of the GC, were distanced on the descent of the Envalira.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the climb of the Beixalis, several contenders attempted to attack but the other contenders were able to follow each time.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The GC group finished around five minutes down on Kuss.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Alexey Lutsenko (Astana–Premier Tech), who was seventh on GC, lost 29 seconds while Martin and Cattaneo conceded four and five minutes, respectively.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar retained a lead of more than five minutes to keep the *maillot jaune* ahead of the second rest day.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The sixteenth stage of the race was another transition stage as the race headed into the Pyrenees.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Much like stage 14, it took a while before a break formed before a trio of riders built a gap after the first climb.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] An 11-man chase group formed just before the intermediate sprint with the peloton letting them go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On the second climb of Col de la Core, Patrick Konrad (Bora–Hansgrohe) bridged up from the chase group to the trio up front before eventually attacking solo from the third climb of the day, the Col de Portet-d'Aspet.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He soloed the rest of the day to win his team's second stage, 42 seconds ahead of Sonny Colbrelli (Team Bahrain Victorious).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The peloton enjoyed a quiet day but Cofidis and van Aert instigated an attack on the Côte d'Aspret-Sarrat, causing a split in the peloton; however, all the contenders made it to the front group and all of them finished together.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The seventeenth stage featured the first of two consecutive summit finishes as the riders tackled two first-category climbs and the *hors catégorie* Col de Portet in the final 62.5 kilometres (38.8 mi).
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] On Bastille Day, French riders composed four of the six riders in the break, gaining an advantage of more than eight minutes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Two riders, Anthony Perez (Cofidis) and Dorian Godon (AG2R Citroën Team), proved themselves as the strongest from the break as the duo led by four minutes heading into the final climb, the Col du Portet.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Perez dropped Godon further up the climb, but UAE Team Emirates chased him down.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 8.5 kilometres (5.3 mi) to go, Pogačar attacked, catching Perez and bringing some of the contenders with him.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] He launched another acceleration a few moments later and this time, only Vingegaard and Carapaz could follow him.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar and Vingegaard worked together while Carapaz sat in their wheels.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Near the *flamme rouge*, Carapaz launched his move, dropping Vingegaard while Pogačar immediately went to his wheel.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Vingegaard slowly made his way back to set up a sprint for the win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 100 metres (330 ft) to go, Pogačar made his move, distancing his companions to win his second stage of the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Vingegaard finished three seconds behind and one second ahead of Carapaz.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The other contenders lost at least a minute and a half to the trio, who comprised the GC podium at the end of the day.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The next day was the final day in the mountains, with the riders tackling the Col du Tourmalet before a summit finish at Luz Ardiden.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] A break immediately formed at the start but they were not allowed to build a lead of more than two minutes.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] As the Tourmalet started, several riders bridged up to the break up front while the INEOS Grenadiers controlled the peloton and kept the break in check.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] From behind, Urán began to struggle, eventually losing nine minutes on the day.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] At the top of the Tourmalet, only two riders were left at the front as David Gaudu (Groupama–FDJ) and Pierre Latour (Team TotalEnergies) led by around half a minute ahead of a chase group composed of Poels and Woods.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Gaudu pushed on the descent while the peloton swept up the remnants of the break.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] 9 kilometres (5.6 mi) from the top of Luz Ardiden, Gaudu was caught.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] With 3.3 kilometres (2.1 mi) left, Pogačar launched his attack, followed by Vingegaard, Carapaz, Mas, and Kuss.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Inside the final kilometre, Mas attacked twice but he would be caught both times.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] After catching Mas a second time, Pogačar pushed on, eventually taking his second successive stage win.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Vingegaard and Carapaz finished two seconds down while the other contenders lost between half a minute to a minute.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar also took the polka-dot jersey after acquiring 80 points with his two consecutive stage wins.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The nineteenth stage featured a flat parcours.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Two crashes took place at the start of the stage but no riders were seriously hurt.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Only six riders comprised the break before being joined by 14 other riders with 100 kilometres (62 mi) to go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The peloton chased hard but the break gradually increased their advantage before the peloton called off the chase.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The attacks started with 45 kilometres (28 mi) left before Mohorič went away with 25 kilometres (16 mi) to go.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The chase group were not able to work together as Mohorič slowly built his gap.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Mohorič soloed to his second stage win while the peloton crossed the line 21 minutes down.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The GC remained unchanged ahead of the final time trial.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The penultimate stage was a 30.8-kilometre (19.1 mi) individual time trial.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Stefan Bissegger (EF Education–Nippo) set the early benchmark time of 36' 37" before Kasper Asgreen (Deceuninck–Quick-Step) beat Bissegger's time by 23 seconds.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Küng threatened Asgreen's time at the first time check but he faded towards the end.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Asgreen's time stood until van Aert beat his time by 21 seconds.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] His time would not be beaten as he won his second stage of the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the battle for the GC placings, all riders in the top ten kept their positions.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Vingegaard finished with the third best time, 32 seconds behind van Aert, to confirm his second place on GC.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Meanwhile, Pogačar avoided taking any risks, eventually finishing with the eighth best time as he put himself on the cusp of winning his second successive Tour title.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The final stage featured the traditional sprint stage to Champs-Élysées.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The first part of the stage was ridden as a procession, with no riders attacking off the front.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] The race started in earnest as they passed through the finish line for the first time.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Several breakaways were attempted but the stage would eventually come down to a sprint finish.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] In the final sprint to the line, Mike Teunissen (Team Jumbo–Visma) managed to lead out his teammate, van Aert, who managed to hold off Philipsen and Cavendish to win his second consecutive stage and his third overall in the race.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] All riders finished safely as 141 riders completed the race, 43 less than the number of riders who started in Brest.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Pogačar won his second successive Tour title as well as winning the mountain and young riders classification for the second year running.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Cavendish won his second points classification title while Team Bahrain Victorious won the teams classification.
[src:brest-france/2021-tour-de-france-p01] Franck Bonnamour (B&B Hotels p/b KTM) won the overall combativity award after featuring in several breakaways.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The history of Brest during the Middle Ages is the history of its castle.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] By the early modern period, however, Brest had become a military harbour, which Richelieu established in 1631.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest subsequently grew around its arsenal until the second part of the 20th century.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Heavily damaged by Allied bombing raids during World War II, the city centre was completely rebuilt after the war.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] At the end of the 20th century and the beginning of the 21st century, the deindustrialization of the city was followed by the development of the service sector.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Nowadays, Brest is an important university town with 23,000 students.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest's history since the 17th century has been linked to the sea: the *Académie de Marine* (Naval Academy) was founded in 1752 in this city.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* was built there.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Every four years, Brest hosts the international festival of the sea, boats and sailors: it is a meeting of old riggings from around the world (*Les Tonnerres de Brest*).
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In the 4th century AD, Brest was known as *Osismis*, as attested in the *Notitia Dignitatum*.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Breton Latin sources of the early Middle Ages also refer to the settlement as *urbs Ocismorum*, using the old name of the tribe of the Osismii.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The city is then recorded as *Bresta* in 856 AD.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The etymology is uncertain, but it may be related to *bre* ('hill').
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest's fortress appears to have remained underdeveloped in the early 11th century.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] It was thereafter gradually strengthened by the Breton dukes, and became a key defensive and political stronghold.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1196, it sheltered the young Arthur of Brittany.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In the 13th century, Brest became fully integrated into ducal control, when Duke John I purchased the castle, town, and port.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1240, Harvey V, Lord of Léon ceded it to John I, Duke of Brittany.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1342, John IV, Duke of Brittany surrendered Brest to the English, in whose possession it was to remain until 1397.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] This was strategically important to the English as it helped protect their communication with Gascony.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Starting in 1534 Brest and the rest of Brittany become fully part of France as the Province of Brittany.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The advantages of Brest's situation as a seaport town were first recognized by Cardinal Richelieu, who in 1631 constructed a harbour with wooden wharves.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] This soon became a base for the French Navy.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Jean-Baptiste Colbert, finance minister under Louis XIV, rebuilt the wharves in masonry and otherwise improved the harbour.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] These fortifications, and with them the naval importance of the town, were to continue to develop throughout the 18th century.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1694, an Anglo-Dutch squadron under Lord Berkeley was soundly defeated in its attack on Brest.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] During the repression of January and February 1894, the gendarmes conducted raids targeting the anarchists living there, without much success.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] They notably surrounded the house of Régis Meunier with their bayonnets fixed.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1917, during the First World War, Brest was used as the disembarking port for many of the troops coming from the United States.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Thousands of such men came through the port on their way to the front lines.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The United States Navy established a naval air station on 13 February 1918 to operate seaplanes.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] This port also became a hot spot where the U.S.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Navy and the French Navy engaged in underwater combat with German submarines.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The base closed shortly after the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In the Second World War, the Germans maintained a large U-boat submarine base at Brest.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Despite being within range of RAF bombers, it was also a base for some of the German surface fleet, giving repair facilities and direct access to the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] For much of 1941, *Scharnhorst*, *Gneisenau* and *Prinz Eugen* were under repair in the dockyards.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The repair yard facilities for both submarines and surface vessels were staffed by both German and French workers, with the latter forming the major part of the workforce; huge reliance was made on this French component.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1944, after the Allied invasion of Normandy, the city was almost totally destroyed during the Battle for Brest, with only a tiny number of buildings left standing.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] After the war, the West German government paid several billion Deutschmarks in reparations to the homeless and destitute civilians of Brest in compensation for the destruction of their city.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Large parts of today's rebuilt city consist of utilitarian granite and concrete buildings.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The French naval base now houses the Brest Naval Training Centre.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] During the postwar Nuremberg Trials, a memorandum of German admiral and *Seekriegsleitung* chief of staff Kurt Fricke from 1940 was given in evidence which suggested that the town should serve as a German enclave after the war.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1972, the French Navy opened its nuclear weapon-submarine (deterrence) base at Île Longue in the *Rade de Brest* (Brest roadstead).
[src:brest-france/brest-france] This continues to be an important base for the French nuclear-armed ballistic missile submarines.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The coat of arms of Brest is divided in two: to the left, there's the three fleurs-de-lis of the former kingdom of France, and to the right it has the ermines of the Duchy of Brittany.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] These arms were used for the first time in a register of deliberations of the city council dated the 15 July 1683.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Additionally, it looks visually identical to the coat of arms of Bourg-la-Reine.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The *Musée de la Tour Tanguy*, in the Tanguy tower, houses a collection of dioramas that depict the city of Brest on the eve of World War II.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The *Musée national de la Marine de Brest*, housed in the ancient castle, contains exhibits which outline Brest's maritime tradition, as well as an aquarium, the Océanopolis marine centre.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The city also has a notable botanical garden specializing in endangered species, the *Conservatoire botanique national de Brest*, as well as the *Jardin botanique de l'Hôpital d'Instruction des Armées Clermont-Tonnerre*.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The city of Brest does not have much remaining historical architecture, apart from a few select monuments such as the castle and the Tanguy tower.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] This is due to heavy bombing by the Allies during World War II, in an attempt to destroy the submarine base the Germans had built in the harbour.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In the 1950s, the town was hastily rebuilt using a large amount of concrete.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In Recouvrance, the west bank of the town, there remains an authentic street of the 17th century, Saint-Malo Street.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] A few kilometres out of town, there are landscapes, from sandy beaches to grottos to tall granite cliffs.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Sunbathing, windsurfing, yachting and fishing are enjoyed in the area.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest was an important warship-producing port during the Napoleonic wars.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The naval port, which is in great part excavated in the rock, extends along both banks of the Penfeld river.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest is located amidst a dramatic landscape near the entrance of the natural *rade de Brest* (Brest roadstead), at the west end of Brittany.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] It is situated to the north of a magnificent landlocked bay, and occupies the slopes of two hills divided by the river Penfeld.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The part of the town on the left bank is regarded as Brest proper, while the part on the right is known as Recouvrance.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] There are also extensive suburbs to the east of the town.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The hillsides are in some places so steep that the ascent from the lower to the upper town has to be effected by flights of steps and the second or third storey of one house is often on a level with the ground storey of the next.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest experiences an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*).
[src:brest-france/brest-france] As a result of maritime moderation, Brest has cool summers by French standards, July afternoons are cooler than the norm in Western Europe.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Rainfall is common year-round, but snowfall is a rarer occurrence since temperatures usually remain several degrees above freezing during winter nights.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] An extreme temperature of 39.3 °C (102.7 °F) was recorded on 18 July 2022.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 1945 Brest absorbed three neighbouring communes.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The population data for 1936 and earlier in the table and graph below refer to the pre-1945 borders.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The railway station of Brest, Gare de Brest, is linked to Rennes and Paris and provides services to other stations in Brittany as well.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] TGV trains to Paris take approximately three hours and forty minutes to reach the capital.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] A new 28-stop, 14.3 km (9 mi) tram line connecting Porte de Plouzané in the west with Porte de Gouesnou and Porte de Guipavas northeast of the city centre opened in June 2012.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest international airport, Brest Bretagne Airport, is mainly linked to Paris, London, Nice, Lyon, Dublin.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The primary operator is Air France (via its subsidiary HOP!).
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest international airport is the main airport of the region of Brittany in terms of passenger traffic with 45% of this traffic of the region, representing 919,404 passengers in 2010.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] A new terminal has been in service since 12 December 2007 and can accommodate up to 1.8 million passengers annually.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The harbour of Brest is mainly dedicated to bulk, hydrocarbon and freight containers.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The harbour's facilities can accommodate the largest modern ships.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] A cruise ship port is also located in Brest, near the city centre.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Due to its location, Brest is regarded as the first French port that can be accessed from the Americas.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Shipping is big business, although Nantes and Saint-Nazaire offer much larger docks and attract more of the larger vessels.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest has the ninth French commercial harbour including ship repairs and maintenance.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The protected location of Brest means that its harbour is ideal to receive any type of ship, from the smallest dinghy to the biggest aircraft carrier (USS *Nimitz* has visited a few times).
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Naval construction is also an important activity: for example, the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* was built by Direction des Constructions Navales (DCN) in Brest.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Despite its image of an industrialised city whose activity depends mainly on military order, the service sector represents 75% of the economic activity.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The importance of the service sector is still increasing while industrialised activity is decaying, explaining the unchanged rate of working-class in Brest.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest also hosts headquarters for many subsidiaries like the banking group Arkéa.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Research and conception is taking an increasing importance.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest claims to be the largest European centre for sciences and techniques linked to the sea: 60% of the French research in the maritime field is based in Brest.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest has a vast program, combining a restructuring of the city, up to 2025.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The Hôtel de Ville (City Hall) was officially opened in 1961.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Breton is not commonly spoken in the city of Brest, which was the only French-speaking city in western Brittany before the 1789 French Revolution, despite the surrounding countryside being fully Breton-speaking at that time.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Like other French minority languages, Breton does not have any official language status in France.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The municipality launched a linguistic plan to revive Breton as a language through *Ya d'ar brezhoneg* on 16 June 2006.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 2008, 1.94% of primary-school children attended French-Breton bilingual Diwan schools.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Besides bilingual schools, the Breton language is also taught in some schools and universities.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The association *Sked* federates all Breton cultural activities.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The city is host to several events to celebrate its long maritime history.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The largest of these is held every four years, when the town organises a tall ship meeting.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The last such tall ship event was "Les Tonnerres de Brest 2016".
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic the next event is planned for 2022.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest also hosts an annual short film festival called "Brest European Short Film Festival".
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The city was the setting for the 1982 art film *Querelle*, directed by Rainer Werner Fassbinder, itself based on the 1947 novel *Querelle de Brest* by Jean Genet.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brittany's most famous local delicacy, the Breton crêpe, is the main culinary feature apart from seafood.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] There are many crêpe restaurants (called *crêperies*).
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Traditional biscuits include *Traou Mad*, which is a full-fat butter biscuit similar to Scottish shortbread.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest has held the Grands Départs of the Tour de France on three occasions, in 1952, 1974 and 2008.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The 2021 Tour de France started from Brest on 26 June 2021.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Stage 6 of the 2018 Tour de France departed from Brest.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Since 1901, Brest has served as the midpoint for the 1,200 km (750 mi) bicycle endurance event, Paris–Brest–Paris.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest is home to Stade Brestois 29 (commonly known as *Brest*), a football team in Ligue 1, the top tier of the French football league system.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest made their debut in European competitions in the 2024/2025 UCL season, after achieving a third-place finish in Ligue 1 a year earlier.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] Brest is also home to Brest Albatros Hockey, an ice hockey team in Ligue Magnus, and won the league title in the 1996 and 1997.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] In 2002 the Brest throwball team Brest LC reached the 1st division of French throwball but were subsequently relegated due to financial difficulty.
[src:brest-france/brest-france] The club has recently adopted an Irish influenced infrastructure.
